    <title>Lee Daniels’ The Deliverance can’t pray away the demons in new trailer</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Jv3B2MIPFD_6wT1HdRld6fTfwJc=/657x0:2871x1476/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73464004/The_Deliverance_u_00_52_26_18_R.0.jpeg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Courtesy of Netflix © 2024&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="IJPP8I"&gt;Though director &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/7/7508443/empire-fox-lee-daniels-hip-hop-music-industry-terrence-howard"&gt;Lee Daniels&lt;/a&gt; isn’t exactly &lt;a href="https://people.com/movies/monique-teams-up-with-lee-daniels-in-first-trailer-horror-film/"&gt;new to horror&lt;/a&gt;, the first trailer for Netflix’s &lt;em&gt;The Deliverance &lt;/em&gt;makes it seem like he’s hitting his stride with the genre.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="qHDsm6"&gt;Inspired by the &lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.indystar.com%2Fstory%2Fnews%2F2019%2F02%2F16%2Fzak-bagans-demon-house-real-story-10-things-know-gary-indiana-latoya-ammons%2F2430585002%2F&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F24199694%2Fnetflix-the-deliverance-trailer-lee-daniels" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;2011 reports of a haunting in Gary, Indiana&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;em&gt;The Deliverance &lt;/em&gt;tells the story of Ebony Jackson (Andra Day), a woman from Pennsylvania whose life is upended as her sons Andre (Anthony B. Jenkins) and Nate (Caleb McLaughlin) are tormented by a malevolent entity. &lt;/p&gt;
